  "prompt": "What are bit vectors?",
  "response": "Bit vectors (or bitvectors) are data structures that efficiently store and manipulate sets of binary flags or boolean values using individual bits. Here's a comprehensive overview:\n\n1. Basic Concept:\n- A bit vector uses individual bits to represent binary states\n- Each bit represents a boolean value (0 or 1)\n- Compact way to store multiple boolean flags in a single integer/array\n\n2. Key Characteristics:\n- Space-efficient: Uses minimal memory\n- Fast operations: Bitwise operations are very quick\n- Typically implemented using integers or arrays of integers\n\n3. Common Operations:\n- Set bit: Mark a specific position as 1\n- Clear bit: Set a specific position to 0\n- Toggle bit: Flip a bit's value\n- Check bit: Determine if a bit is set\n\n4. Example Bitwise Operations:\n```cpp\n// Set bit\nx |= (1 << position)\n\n// Clear bit\nx &= ~(1 << position)\n\n// Toggle bit\nx ^= (1 << position)\n\n// Check bit\nbool isSet = (x & (1 << position)) != 0\n```\n\n5. Use Cases:\n- Flags and configuration settings\n- Efficient set representations\n- Permissions management\n- Compact data storage\n- Algorithmic optimizations\n\n6. Benefits:\n- Memory efficiency\n- Fast computations\n- Low overhead\n\nExample implementation in C++:\n```cpp\nclass BitVector {\nprivate:\n    std::vector<uint64_t> bits;\n\npublic:\n    void setBit(int position) {\n        bits[position / 64] |= (1ULL << (position % 64));\n    }\n\n    bool getBit(int position) {\n        return (bits[position / 64] & (1ULL << (position % 64))) != 0;\n    }\n};\n```",
